06053nam a22010455i 9781512825190DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815128251907 a10.9783/97815128251902doi  a(DE-B1597)650956  a(OCoLC)1381710576  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHT169.P32bI835 2023 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a307.1/21609549149223/eng/202310261 aMoatasim, Faiza, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaster Plans and Encroachments :bThe Architecture of Informality in Islamabad /cFaiza Moatasim. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe City in the Twenty-First Century00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tA NOTE ON TRANSLITERATION AND TRANSLATION -- tIntroduction: Making Master Plans and Encroachments -- tCHAPTER 1 Model Villages in a Modern City -- tCHAPTER 2 Ordinary Informality -- tCHAPTER 3 Long-Term Temporariness -- tCHAPTER 4 Elite Informality -- tCHAPTER 5 Non-conforming Uses -- tConclusion: Contingent Plans -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong urban designers and municipal officials, the term encroachment is defined as a deviation from the official master plan. But in cities today, such informal modifications to the urban fabric are deeply enmeshed with formal planning procedures. Master Plans and Encroachments examines informality in the high-modernist city of Islamabad as a strategic conformity to official schemes and regulations rather than as a deviation from them.For the new administrative capital of Pakistan designed in 1959 by Greek architect and planner Constantinos A. Doxiadis, Islamabad’s master plan offers a clear template of formal urban design within which informal spaces and processes have been articulated. Drawing on deep archival research, wide-ranging interviews, and an array of visual material, including photographs, maps, and architectural drawings, Faiza Moatasim shows how Islamabad’s master plan is not simply a blueprint that guides future urban development or makes its violations apparent; it is used by both city officials and citizens to develop informal spaces that accommodate unfulfilled needs and desires of those living and working in the city.Master Plans and Encroachments is the first book that examines the informal practices of both the privileged and the underprivileged. The book highlights how low-, middle-, and upper-income people do not randomly build informal spaces; they strategically use architectural techniques to support their informal claims to space, which are often met with the government’s tacit approval. By focusing on those spaces in Islamabad’s urban fabric that are not part of its official master plan, the book demonstrates how planning actually works in complex ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecturezPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aCity planningzPakistanzIslāmābād. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh  a1950s.  aConstantinos A. Doxiadis.  aElite.  aEncroachment.  aGlobal South.  aInformality.  aIslamabad.  aPakistan.  aPlan.  aaesthetics.  aarchitecture.  ablueprint.  abusiness.  acapital.  acity cities.  adevelopment.  aforms.  agovernance.  ahomes.  ainformal spaces.  ainteriors.  alaw.  alayout.  amaps.  amaster plan.  amodernism.  anegotiation.  aphotographs.  aprivilege.  aregulations.  astalls.  astreet vendors.  atechnique.  atwentieth century.  aurban studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package: